[1mFAST-FORWARD MERGE[0m
     Often  the  current branch head is an ancestor of the named commit. This is the most common case especially when invoked from [1mgit pull[22m: you are tracking an upstream repository, you
     have committed no local changes, and now you want to update to a newer upstream revision. In this case, a new commit is not needed to store the combined history; instead, the  [1mHEAD[0m
     (along with the index) is updated to point at the named commit, without creating an extra merge commit.

